explanation: To determine compliance with the MISRA rule on well-formed for loops you must inspect any code that could introduce or affect for-loop behavior in the target function. The target function itself has no explicit for statements, but the MISRA rule treats the behaviour of functions called inside loop clauses/body as part of the loop semantics. Therefore the analysis requires: 1) All directly called functions (OS_ObjectIdToType_Impl, OS_TaskGetId_Impl, OS_ObjectIdGetById, OS_ObjectIdTransferToken, OS_TimeBaseLock_Impl, OS_ObjectIdFromToken, OS_ObjectIdEqual, OS_TimeBaseUnlock_Impl, OS_ObjectIdFinalizeDelete, OS_ObjectIdRelease, OS_ObjectIdDefined, OS_TimeBaseDelete) so their implementations can be checked for any for loops or side-effects that would violate the rule. 2) The immediate callees of OS_ObjectIdGetById and OS_ObjectIdFinalizeDelete/Release/TimeBaseDelete (OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit, OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex, OS_ObjectIdConvertToken, OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel, OS_ObjectIndexFromToken, OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish, OS_NotifyEvent, OS_TimeBaseDelete_Impl) because these are called transitively and may contain for loops or modify objects used as loop counters/flags. 3) All macros, global tables and constants referenced by the function (OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET, OS_timecb_table, OS_timebase_table, OS_OBJECT_ID_UNDEFINED, TIMECB_FLAG_DEDICATED_TIMEBASE, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_TIMEBASE, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_TIMECB, OS_LOCK_MODE_EXCLUSIVE, OS_LOCK_MODE_NONE) because macros or table accessors can expand to loops or generate side-effects relevant to MISRA analysis. 4) The types and object definitions (OS_object_token_t, OS_timebase_internal_record_t, OS_timecb_internal_record_t, osal_id_t, osal_objtype_t) because their members (e.g., next_cb/prev_cb/first_cb/flags/timebase_token) are used in expressions that would be part of loop conditions or increment expressions if a for loop existed; knowing their types and access semantics is necessary to judge whether an expression uses/modifies objects disallowed by the rule. Each listed symbol must be inspected to ensure no hidden for-loops, no side-effects in loop-condition-like expressions, and that no called routine modifies a potential loop counter or loop-control flag in the loop body.
